# Backend Rules

## Purpose
Standardize NestJS implementation for RE-OS API and workers per `docs/CODING_STANDARDS.md`.

## Requirements
- TypeScript strict; DTOs with class-validator on all inputs.
- `@RequirePermissions()` on every controller method.
- `JwtAuthGuard`, `TenantGuard`, `PermissionsGuard` order enforced globally.
- Services own transactions (`@Transactional()` or explicit query runner).
- Map entities to response DTOs — never leak password_hash, internal fields.
- Structured JSON logging with `tenant_id`, `user_id`, `trace_id`.

## Restrictions
- No `any` in service public methods.
- No raw SQL without security review and parameterization.
- No synchronous email/ES indexing in request path — queue jobs.
- No business rules only in frontend.

## Best Practices
- Repository base class: `findManyScoped(tenantId, filters)`.
- Idempotency keys on webhook and payment handlers.
- Unit test services with mocked repositories.
- OpenAPI decorators on all endpoints.

## Anti-Patterns
- Passing `tenant_id` from request body (use JWT/context only).
- Catching all errors and returning 200.
- Importing TypeORM/Prisma in controllers.

## Examples

```typescript
@Post()
@RequirePermissions('employees.create')
async create(@Body() dto: CreateEmployeeDto, @CurrentUser() user: AuthUser) {
  const data = await this.employeeService.create(dto, user);
  return { data, meta: { request_id: user.requestId } };
}
```
